UKONGA Prison Hospital has received medical equipment from the Rotary Club of Dar es Salaam worth 6m/- aimed at addressing challenges of providing intensive care to critically ill and poor people, who can afford such services. Speaking at the occasion to receive the equipment, Chief Medical Officer Abdillatif Mkingule unveiled the equipment as three gas cylinders, 40- bed sheets, 6 wheelchairs and related items, which assist doctors in providing care to patients. “The equipment would go a long way in alleviating the various challenges facing patients who come here for treatment, especially those in need of urgent care,” said Mkingule. Dr Mkingule said the rotary medical camp has been of great help to them, especially with two years supporting them with various hospital equipment. He also said the Club has enabled them to get some drugs and medical equipment that were in high demand in the facility. “These medical devices have been a challenge in our hospital, especially gas cylinders, especially in this period when efforts are needed to contain Covid-19 pandemic,” said Dr Mkingule. On her side, the rotary president Aisha Sykes said; “We have come here to hand over various medical equipment as there has been a great need for this equipment at this hospital in Ukonga.” Ms Sykes said that the club is not only providing the medical equipment, but it has also been providing various services at Ukonga hospital including free malaria treatment services. She also said that it was not the first time for them to provide medical supplies to the hospital in Ukonga, adding that last year; they donated various medical equipment and set up a health camp in the institution.